ODE XVI

‘ REST is (at times at least) the prayer of all men, though they do not go the way to find it. Gold and purple will not buy it, Grosphus; neither wealth nor rank banish care; and meantime very little suffices for a happy life if the heart is free from fear and desire. Moderated desires, not hurrying from place to place, are the means to avoid care. Go where you will you cannot escape yourself. Care boards the bestappointed yacht and keeps up with the fleetest horseman. Enjoy the present, and don’t think of the future. If troubles come, smile and be patient and they will be the lighter. Unmixed happiness is not to be looked for: Achilles
